        <p className="text-slate-600">
          Under the UTSA, information must meet all three criteria simultaneously to qualify for trade secret protection. If any pillar falls, the protection collapses.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div className="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-3 gap-6 relative">
        {/* Element 1 */}
        <div className="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-100 rounded-xl p-6 relative z-10 flex flex-col items-center text-center">
          <div className="w-16 h-16 bg-blue-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center mb-4 shadow-sm">
            <FileText size={32} />
          </div>
          <h3 className="text-lg font-bold text-blue-900 mb-2">1. Information</h3>
          <p className="text-sm text-blue-800 mb-4">
            Must be concrete, definable content (not a vague idea).
          </p>
          <ul className="text-sm text-blue-700 space-y-1 text-left w-full bg-white/50 p-3 rounded-lg">
            <li>• Formulas & Recipes</li>
            <li>• Algorithms & Programs</li>
            <li>• Compilations (Customer lists)</li>
            <li>• Methods & Techniques</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        {/* Connector (Desktop only) */}
        <div className="hidden md:flex absolute top-1/2 left-[20%] right-[20%] h-1 bg-blue-100 -translate-y-1/2 z-0"></div>

        {/* Element 2 */}
        <div className="bg-emerald-50 border border-emerald-100 rounded-xl p-6 relative z-10 flex flex-col items-center text-center">
          <div className="w-16 h-16 bg-emerald-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center mb-4 shadow-sm">
            <DollarSign size={32} />
          </div>
          <h3 className="text-lg font-bold text-emerald-900 mb-2">2. Economic Value</h3>
          <p className="text-sm text-emerald-800 mb-4">
            Must derive value specifically from being kept hidden.
          </p>
          <ul className="text-sm text-emerald-700 space-y-1 text-left w-full bg-white/50 p-3 rounded-lg">
            <li>• Not generally known</li>
            <li>• Not readily ascertainable</li>
            <li>• Grants a competitive edge</li>
            <li>• Costly/difficult to replicate</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        {/* Element 3 */}
        <div className="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-100 rounded-xl p-6 relative z-10 flex flex-col items-center text-center">
          <div className="w-16 h-16 bg-amber-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center mb-4 shadow-sm">
            <Lock size={32} />
          </div>
          <h3 className="text-lg font-bold text-amber-900 mb-2">3. Reasonable Efforts</h3>
          <p className="text-sm text-amber-800 mb-4">
            The owner must actively treat the information as a secret.
          </p>
          <ul className="text-sm text-amber-700 space-y-1 text-left w-full bg-white/50 p-3 rounded-lg">
            <li>• Non-Disclosure Agreements</li>
            <li>• Password protections</li>
            <li>• Need-to-know access controls</li>
            <li>• "Confidential" markings</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div className="mt-8 bg-slate-100 p-6 rounded-xl border border-slate-200 text-center">
        <h4 className="font-bold text-slate-800 flex items-center justify-center gap-2 mb-2">
          <Shield className="text-blue-600" /> The Result: Trade Secret Protection
        </h4>
        <p className="text-sm text-slate-600">
          Unlike patents, protection lasts indefinitely as long as these three elements are maintained. There is no expiration date, but a single public disclosure can destroy it instantly.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
